## Pattern 4: Error Handling

**Problem**: Different error types require different handling

**Solution**: Use typed error classes from Axios interceptor

**Implementation**:

```typescript
// In component or hook
import {
  AuthenticationError,
  ValidationError,
  NotFoundError,
} from '@/core/services/api/types/api-error';

try {
  await bookService.create(bookData);
  toast.success('Tạo sách thành công');
} catch (error) {
  if (error instanceof ValidationError) {
    // Show field-specific errors
    Object.entries(error.errors).forEach(([field, messages]) => {
      toast.error(`${field}: ${messages.join(', ')}`);
    });
  } else if (error instanceof AuthenticationError) {
    // Redirect to login (usually handled by interceptor)
    router.push('/login');
  } else if (error instanceof NotFoundError) {
    toast.error('Sách không tồn tại');
  } else {
    // Generic error
    toast.error('Đã xảy ra lỗi, vui lòng thử lại');
    console.error('Unexpected error:', error);
  }
}
```

**Error Types** (defined in `src/core/services/api/types/api-error.ts`):
- `NetworkError`: No network connection
- `AuthenticationError`: 401 (handled by interceptor, rarely seen)
- `AuthorizationError`: 403 (permission denied)
- `ValidationError`: 422 (form validation errors)
- `NotFoundError`: 404
- `MethodNotAllowedError`: 405
- `ServerError`: 500+

**Best Practices**:
- ✅ Use typed error checks (`instanceof`)
- ✅ Show user-friendly messages
- ✅ Log technical details to console (development)
- ✅ Send critical errors to monitoring (production)
- ❌ Don't show stack traces to users
- ❌ Don't catch errors silently

